# Redo: World-Class Cinematic Synchronization

This incredibly ambitious plan shifts the Remotion architecture from a mechanical slideshow into a world-class, word-perfect documentary. The goal is brutal synchronization: images and effects will mathematically lock onto the exact milliseconds of specific spoken words using true algorithmic alignment.

## User Review Required

> [!CAUTION]
> This represents a total paradigm shift from the previous setups. We are ditching the `trump-iran-apr14` rigid template and building a bespoke cinematic engine that uses exact ElevenLabs API millisecond timestamps to orchestrate visual cues and kinetic typography. 
> Please review the architecture and verify if this meets your "world class production value" standard before I execute.

## Phase 1: Environment & API Upgrades
- **Create `.env`**: I will generate the `.env` file to securely store your `ELEVENLABS_API_KEY` and `TAVILY_API_KEY`.
- **True Timestamps API (`generate-voiceover-sync.ts`)**: I will replace the script to hit the newer `POST /v1/text-to-speech/{voice_id}/with-timestamps` API. This will intercept the raw base64 audio and the **exact character/word boundaries**, constructing flawless `.json` maps down to the millisecond. No more approximations.

## Phase 2: Semantic Media Mapping Engine
- I will abandon the mechanical `2.8-second` visual slice logic.
- Instead, I will write an intelligent parsing layer inside `Main.tsx` that maps specific media to specific *semantic words* in the voiceover loop.
  - E.g. When the voiceover says **"Fred"** (measured dynamically from `startMs`), the composition instantly hard-cuts to `13FREDweb1-videoSixteenByNineJumbo1600.jpg`.
  - When the voiceover hits **"New York Military Academy"**, it hard-cuts strictly to `Donald_Trump_NYMA.jpg`.
  - When the voiceover hits **"Trump Tower"**, it hard-cuts to `Waterfall_in_Trump_Tower_2.jpg`.
  
## Phase 3: World-Class Cinematic Visuals (`Scene.tsx` & `Typography.tsx`)
Rather than "talking over slides", the framework will leverage complex Remotion styling:
  1. **Split-Depth Ken Burns**: Foreground elements will subtly scale opposite to the background grain to simulate deep parallax. 
  2. **Violent Transitions**: Audio frequency visualization (`useAudioData`) and timeline hooks will trigger frame-perfect flash-cuts and chromatic aberration at major script beats (like "Extortion" or "Dominance").
  3. **Kinetic World-Lock Typography**: Subtitles will no longer just sit in a lower-third box. We will restore `@remotion/captions` using the *flawless* millisecond alignment JSON, blowing the primary word up in the center-stage, utilizing 3D rotation (`transform: rotateX/rotateY`) and vicious spring easing that reacts exactly to the ElevenLabs emphasis.

